  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent, detect, and report money laundering activities. These include:\n\n1. Key Legal Requirements:\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) procedures\n- Customer identification and verification\n- Reporting suspicious transactions\n- Maintaining transaction records\n- Implementing anti-money laundering (AML) compliance programs\n\n2. Regulatory Frameworks:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- International compliance standards\n\n3. Specific Compliance Measures:\n- Conducting customer due diligence\n- Screening customers against watchlists\n- Monitoring transactions for unusual patterns\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Implementing risk-based assessment procedures\n\n4. Potential Consequences of Non-Compliance:\n- Significant financial penalties\n- Criminal prosecution\n- Loss of banking licenses\n- Reputational damage\n\n5. Required Reporting:\n- Currency Transaction Reports\n- Suspicious Activity Reports\n- Cross-border transfer documentation\n\nFinancial institutions must continuously update their AML procedures to meet evolving regulatory requirements and combat sophisticated financial crimes.",
